      <h2 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"> <span class="mw-headline" id="Setting">Setting</span></h2>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Whereas the novel and the 1985 film were set in Chile, with Neruda living in his home at <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isla_Negra" title="Isla Negra">Isla Negra</a> around 1970, <i>Il Postino</i> moves the setting to Italy in about 1950. The film is set and was partially filmed on the island of <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salina_Island" title="Salina Island">Salina</a>, of the volcanic <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aeolian_Islands" title="Aeolian Islands">Aeolian Island</a> chain off the north coast of Sicily. One unfortunate victim of the film's popularity has been Pollara Beach on the island, which has suffered erosion from motorboats and vandalism from tourists since the film was produced.</p>
      <h2 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"> <span class="mw-headline" id="Soundtrack">Soundtrack</span></h2>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">In 1994 to promote the movie, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miramax" title="Miramax">Miramax</a> published <i>The Postman (Il Postino): Music From The Miramax Motion Picture</i>, which besides the film's score, composed by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luis_Enr%C3%ADquez_Bacalov" title="Luis EnrÃ­quez Bacalov">Luis EnrÃ­quez Bacalov</a>, includes Neruda's poems recited by many celebrities. There are a total of 31 tracks.</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The album won the <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Original_Score" title="Academy Award for Best Original Score">Academy Award for Best Original Dramatic Score</a> and the <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BAFTA_Award_for_Best_Film_Music" title="BAFTA Award for Best Film Music">BAFTA Award for Best Film Music</a>.</p>
      <h2 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"> <span class="mw-headline" id="Reception">Reception</span></h2>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The movie was very well received. <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotten_Tomatoes" title="Rotten Tomatoes">Rotten Tomatoes</a> reports that 92% of the critics liked the film, based on 25 reviews. It received a score of 81 on <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metacritic" title="Metacritic">Metacritic</a>, indicating "Universal Acclaim", based on 13 critic reviews.</p>
      <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The film won the <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BAFTA_Award_for_Best_Film_Not_in_the_English_Language" title="BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language">BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language</a>. The film's score, composed by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luis_Enr%C3%ADquez_Bacalov" title="Luis EnrÃ­quez Bacalov">Luis EnrÃ­quez Bacalov</a>, won an Academy Award and a BAFTA award. The film was also nominated for <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Actor">Best Actor in a Leading Role</a> (<a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massimo_Troisi" title="Massimo Troisi">Massimo Troisi</a>), <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Directing" title="Academy Award for Directing">Best Director</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Picture" title="Academy Award for Best Picture">Best Picture</a>, and <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Writing_Adapted_Screenplay" title="Academy Award for Writing Adapted Screenplay">Best Writing, Screenplay Based on Material from Another Medium</a>.</p>
